May the one who blessed our ancestors, Abraham, Isaac, and
Jacob, Sarah, Rebekah, Rachel, and Leah, bless 
who has risen today in honor of the /SCS/XXOURCE OF /XXA/XXLL/XX and in honor
of the Torah and Shabbat* (/ITon a Festival, say/XX: the Festival). May
he /she be granted life and kept from every trouble and
affliction, and from every harm and sickness. May he /she be
granted blessing and success in all his / her labors along with all
of Israel, and let us say: Amen./PR

/PR

*At this point in the /ITmi sheberah/±/XX, an additional phrase can easily be added
on occasions for which no special /ITmi sheberah/±/XX appears in this book. Gradua-
tions, the birth of grandchildren, new jobs and many other milestones are
worthy of such public recognition. The /ITgabay/XX may choose to chant part or
all of the /ITmi sheberah/±/XX in English. When Hebrew alone is used, an English
announcement of the occasion is appropriate.    /SC/XXD.A.T./XX/PR

